{"cues": [{"duration": 4.02, "start": 0.0, "text": "[Submit subtitle corrections at criblate.com]"}, {"duration": 2.682, "start": 4.02, "text": "The hard assumption here is that you've watched part 3,"}, {"duration": 3.218, "start": 6.702, "text": "giving an intuitive walkthrough of the backpropagation algorithm."}, {"duration": 3.18, "start": 11.04, "text": "Here we get a little more formal and dive into the relevant calculus."}, {"duration": 2.445, "start": 14.82, "text": "It's normal for this to be at least a little confusing,"}, {"duration": 3.335, "start": 17.265, "text": "so the mantra to regularly pause and ponder certainly applies as much here"}, {"duration": 0.8, "start": 20.6, "text": "as anywhere else."}, {"duration": 3.935, "start": 21.94, "text": "Our main goal is to show how people in machine learning commonly think about"}, {"duration": 2.95, "start": 25.875, "text": "the chain rule from calculus in the context of networks,"}, {"duration": 3.676, "start": 28.825, "text": "which has a different feel from how most introductory calculus courses"}, {"duration": 1.139, "start": 32.501, "text": "approach the subject."}, {"duration": 2.631, "start": 34.34, "text": "For those of you uncomfortable with the relevant calculus,"}, {"duration": 1.769, "start": 36.971, "text": "I do have a whole series on the topic."}, {"duration": 3.061, "start": 39.96, "text": "Let's start off with an extremely simple network,"}, {"duration": 2.999, "start": 43.021, "text": "one where each layer has a single neuron in it."}, {"duration": 3.576, "start": 46.32, "text": "This network is determined by three weights and three biases,"}, {"duration": 4.984, "start": 49.896, "text": "and our goal is to understand how sensitive the cost function is to these variables."}, {"duration": 2.676, "start": 55.42, "text": "That way, we know which adjustments to those terms will"}, {"duration": 2.724, "start": 58.096, "text": "cause the most efficient decrease to the cost function."}, {"duration": 2.88, "start": 61.96, "text": "And we're just going to focus on the connection between the last two neurons."}, {"duration": 4.258, "start": 65.98, "text": "Let's label the activation of that last neuron with a superscript L,"}, {"duration": 5.322, "start": 70.238, "text": "indicating which layer it's in, so the activation of the previous neuron is a^(L-1)."}, {"duration": 3.732, "start": 76.36, "text": "These are not exponents, they're just a way of indexing what we're talking about,"}, {"duration": 2.948, "start": 80.092, "text": "since I want to save subscripts for different indices later on."}, {"duration": 4.23, "start": 83.72, "text": "Let's say that the value we want this last activation to be for"}, {"duration": 4.23, "start": 87.95, "text": "a given training example is y, for example, y might be 0 or 1."}, {"duration": 6.4, "start": 92.84, "text": "So the cost of this network for a single training example is a^(L - y) squared."}, {"duration": 4.12, "start": 100.26, "text": "We'll denote the cost of that one training example as C0."}, {"duration": 3.94, "start": 105.9, "text": "As a reminder, this last activation is determined by a weight,"}, {"duration": 5.402, "start": 109.84, "text": "which I'm going to call w(L), times the previous neuron's activation plus some bias,"}, {"duration": 1.398, "start": 115.242, "text": "which I'll call b(L)."}, {"duration": 3.9, "start": 117.42, "text": "And then you pump that through some special nonlinear function like the sigmoid or ReLU."}, {"duration": 3.642, "start": 121.8, "text": "It's actually going to make things easier for us if we give a special name to"}, {"duration": 3.878, "start": 125.442, "text": "this weighted sum, like z, with the same superscript as the relevant activations."}, {"duration": 4.951, "start": 130.38, "text": "This is a lot of terms, and a way you might conceptualize it is that the weight,"}, {"duration": 4.022, "start": 135.331, "text": "previous action and the bias all together are used to compute z,"}, {"duration": 4.518, "start": 139.353, "text": "which in turn lets us compute a, which finally, along with a constant y,"}, {"duration": 1.609, "start": 143.871, "text": "lets us compute the cost."}, {"duration": 4.658, "start": 147.34, "text": "And of course a(L-1) is influenced by its own weight and bias and such..."}, {"duration": 3.062, "start": 151.998, "text": "but we're not going to focus on that right now."}, {"duration": 1.92, "start": 155.7, "text": "All of these are just numbers, right?"}, {"duration": 2.98, "start": 158.06, "text": "And it can be nice to think of each one as having its own little number line."}, {"duration": 3.463, "start": 161.72, "text": "Our first goal is to understand how sensitive the"}, {"duration": 3.817, "start": 165.183, "text": "cost function is to small changes in our weight w(L)."}, {"duration": 5.32, "start": 169.54, "text": "Or phrased differently, what is the derivative of C with respect to w(L)?"}, {"duration": 5.066, "start": 175.6, "text": "When you see this del w term, think of it as meaning some tiny nudge to W,"}, {"duration": 4.313, "start": 180.666, "text": "like a change by 0.01, and think of this del C term as meaning"}, {"duration": 3.081, "start": 184.979, "text": "whatever the resulting nudge to the cost is."}, {"duration": 2.16, "start": 188.06, "text": "What we want is their ratio."}, {"duration": 4.53, "start": 191.26, "text": "Conceptually, this tiny nudge to w(L) causes some nudge to z(L),"}, {"duration": 5.45, "start": 195.79, "text": "which in turn causes some nudge to a(L), which directly influences the cost."}, {"duration": 5.105, "start": 203.12, "text": "So we break things up by first looking at the ratio of a tiny change to z(L) to"}, {"duration": 4.975, "start": 208.225, "text": "this tiny change w(L), that is, the derivative of z(L) with respect to w(L)."}, {"duration": 3.759, "start": 213.2, "text": "Likewise, you then consider the ratio of the change to a(L) to"}, {"duration": 3.699, "start": 216.959, "text": "the tiny change in z(L) that caused it, as well as the ratio"}, {"duration": 4.002, "start": 220.658, "text": "between the final nudge to C and this intermediate nudge to a(L)."}, {"duration": 4.631, "start": 225.74, "text": "This right here is the chain rule, where multiplying together these"}, {"duration": 4.769, "start": 230.371, "text": "three ratios gives us the sensitivity of C to small changes in w(L)."}, {"duration": 2.682, "start": 236.88, "text": "So on screen right now, there's a lot of symbols,"}, {"duration": 3.339, "start": 239.562, "text": "and take a moment to make sure it's clear what they all are,"}, {"duration": 3.339, "start": 242.901, "text": "because now we're going to compute the relevant derivatives."}, {"duration": 5.72, "start": 247.44, "text": "The derivative of C with respect to a(L) works out to be 2(a(L)-y)."}, {"duration": 4.612, "start": 253.98, "text": "Notice this means its size is proportional to the difference between the network's"}, {"duration": 4.33, "start": 258.592, "text": "output and the thing we want it to be, so if that output was very different,"}, {"duration": 4.218, "start": 262.922, "text": "even slight changes stand to have a big impact on the final cost function."}, {"duration": 4.077, "start": 267.84, "text": "The derivative of a(L) with respect to z(L) is just the derivative"}, {"duration": 4.263, "start": 271.917, "text": "of our sigmoid function, or whatever nonlinearity you choose to use."}, {"duration": 7.44, "start": 277.22, "text": "And the derivative of z(L) with respect to w(L)... In this case comes out to be a(L-1)."}, {"duration": 3.624, "start": 285.76, "text": "Now I don't know about you, but I think it's easy to get stuck head down in the"}, {"duration": 4.036, "start": 289.384, "text": "formulas without taking a moment to sit back and remind yourself of what they all mean."}, {"duration": 4.334, "start": 293.92, "text": "In the case of this last derivative, the amount that the small nudge to the"}, {"duration": 4.566, "start": 298.254, "text": "weight influenced the last layer depends on how strong the previous neuron is."}, {"duration": 4.9, "start": 303.38, "text": "Remember, this is where the neurons-that-fire-together-wire-together idea comes in."}, {"duration": 3.172, "start": 309.2, "text": "And all of this is the derivative with respect to w(L)"}, {"duration": 3.348, "start": 312.372, "text": "only of the cost for a specific single training example."}, {"duration": 3.462, "start": 316.44, "text": "Since the full cost function involves averaging together all"}, {"duration": 3.058, "start": 319.902, "text": "those costs across many different training examples,"}, {"duration": 4.5, "start": 322.96, "text": "its derivative requires averaging this expression over all training examples."}, {"duration": 3.453, "start": 328.38, "text": "And of course, that is just one component of the gradient vector,"}, {"duration": 3.24, "start": 331.833, "text": "which itself is built up from the partial derivatives of the"}, {"duration": 3.187, "start": 335.073, "text": "cost function with respect to all those weights and biases."}, {"duration": 3.198, "start": 340.64, "text": "But even though that's just one of the many partial derivatives we need,"}, {"duration": 1.422, "start": 343.838, "text": "it's more than 50% of the work."}, {"duration": 3.38, "start": 346.34, "text": "The sensitivity to the bias, for example, is almost identical."}, {"duration": 4.98, "start": 350.04, "text": "We just need to change out this del z del w term for a del z del b."}, {"duration": 3.98, "start": 358.42, "text": "And if you look at the relevant formula, that derivative comes out to be 1."}, {"duration": 4.123, "start": 366.14, "text": "Also, and this is where the idea of propagating backwards comes in,"}, {"duration": 5.477, "start": 370.263, "text": "you can see how sensitive this cost function is to the activation of the previous layer."}, {"duration": 4.232, "start": 375.74, "text": "Namely, this initial derivative in the chain rule expression,"}, {"duration": 5.688, "start": 379.972, "text": "the sensitivity of z to the previous activation, comes out to be the weight w(L)."}, {"duration": 3.842, "start": 386.64, "text": "And again, even though we're not going to be able to directly influence"}, {"duration": 3.409, "start": 390.482, "text": "that previous layer activation, it's helpful to keep track of,"}, {"duration": 4.058, "start": 393.891, "text": "because now we can just keep iterating this same chain rule idea backwards"}, {"duration": 4.491, "start": 397.949, "text": "to see how sensitive the cost function is to previous weights and previous biases."}, {"duration": 4.109, "start": 403.18, "text": "And you might think this is an overly simple example, since all layers have one neuron,"}, {"duration": 3.731, "start": 407.289, "text": "and things are going to get exponentially more complicated for a real network."}, {"duration": 4.209, "start": 411.7, "text": "But honestly, not that much changes when we give the layers multiple neurons,"}, {"duration": 2.951, "start": 415.909, "text": "really it's just a few more indices to keep track of."}, {"duration": 3.373, "start": 419.38, "text": "Rather than the activation of a given layer simply being a(L),"}, {"duration": 4.407, "start": 422.753, "text": "it's also going to have a subscript indicating which neuron of that layer it is."}, {"duration": 7.26, "start": 427.16, "text": "Let's use the letter k to index the layer L-1, and j to index the layer L."}, {"duration": 3.307, "start": 435.26, "text": "For the cost, again we look at what the desired output is,"}, {"duration": 4.561, "start": 438.567, "text": "but this time we add up the squares of the differences between these last layer"}, {"duration": 2.052, "start": 443.128, "text": "activations and the desired output."}, {"duration": 4.76, "start": 446.08, "text": "That is, you take a sum over a(L)j minus yj squared."}, {"duration": 4.08, "start": 453.04, "text": "Since there's a lot more weights, each one has to have a couple more"}, {"duration": 3.96, "start": 457.12, "text": "indices to keep track of where it is, so let's call the weight of"}, {"duration": 3.84, "start": 461.08, "text": "the edge connecting this kth neuron to the jth neuron, w(L)_jk."}, {"duration": 2.76, "start": 465.62, "text": "Those indices might feel a little backwards at first,"}, {"duration": 3.803, "start": 468.38, "text": "but it lines up with how you'd index the weight matrix I talked about in"}, {"duration": 0.937, "start": 472.183, "text": "the part 1 video."}, {"duration": 4.261, "start": 473.62, "text": "Just as before, it's still nice to give a name to the relevant weighted sum,"}, {"duration": 4.485, "start": 477.881, "text": "like z, so that the activation of the last layer is just your special function,"}, {"duration": 1.794, "start": 482.366, "text": "like the sigmoid, applied to z."}, {"duration": 4.332, "start": 484.66, "text": "You can see what I mean, where all of these are essentially the same equations we had"}, {"duration": 4.026, "start": 488.992, "text": "before in the one-neuron-per-layer case, it's just that it looks a little more"}, {"duration": 0.662, "start": 493.018, "text": "complicated."}, {"duration": 3.783, "start": 495.44, "text": "And indeed, the chain-ruled derivative expression describing how"}, {"duration": 4.197, "start": 499.223, "text": "sensitive the cost is to a specific weight looks essentially the same."}, {"duration": 2.92, "start": 503.92, "text": "I'll leave it to you to pause and think about each of those terms if you want."}, {"duration": 3.938, "start": 508.98, "text": "What does change here, though, is the derivative of the cost"}, {"duration": 3.742, "start": 512.918, "text": "with respect to one of the activations in the layer L-1."}, {"duration": 2.689, "start": 517.78, "text": "In this case, the difference is that the neuron influences"}, {"duration": 2.411, "start": 520.469, "text": "the cost function through multiple different paths."}, {"duration": 5.539, "start": 524.68, "text": "That is, on the one hand, it influences a(L)0, which plays a role in the cost function,"}, {"duration": 5.411, "start": 530.219, "text": "but it also has an influence on a(L)1, which also plays a role in the cost function,"}, {"duration": 1.91, "start": 535.63, "text": "and you have to add those up."}, {"duration": 3.22, "start": 539.82, "text": "And that, well, that's pretty much it."}, {"duration": 2.783, "start": 543.5, "text": "Once you know how sensitive the cost function is to the"}, {"duration": 3.137, "start": 546.283, "text": "activations in this second-to-last layer, you can just repeat"}, {"duration": 3.44, "start": 549.42, "text": "the process for all the weights and biases feeding into that layer."}, {"duration": 1.06, "start": 553.9, "text": "So pat yourself on the back!"}, {"duration": 4.756, "start": 555.3, "text": "If all of this makes sense, you have now looked deep into the heart of backpropagation,"}, {"duration": 2.624, "start": 560.056, "text": "the workhorse behind how neural networks learn."}, {"duration": 4.886, "start": 563.3, "text": "These chain rule expressions give you the derivatives that determine each component in"}, {"duration": 5.114, "start": 568.186, "text": "the gradient that helps minimize the cost of the network by repeatedly stepping downhill."}, {"duration": 4.095, "start": 574.3, "text": "If you sit back and think about all that, this is a lot of layers of complexity to"}, {"duration": 4.345, "start": 578.395, "text": "wrap your mind around, so don't worry if it takes time for your mind to digest it all."}], "video_id": "tIeHLnjs5U8"}